  "base_commit": "89f42497a9951fbb72ce087dc813ed9973f9e686",
  "pr_number": 1975,
  "issue_number": 1974,
  "issue_title": "Bug: IdentifyRecurringTransactionsJob debounce gate misses 9 of 14 Syncable provider associations",
  "issue_body": "## Before you start (required)\n\n### General checklist\n\n- [x] I have removed personal / sensitive data from screenshots and logs\n- [x] I have searched [existing issues](https://github.com/we-promise/sure/issues?q=is:issue) and [discussions](https://github.com/we-promise/sure/discussions) to ensure this is not a duplicate issue\n\n### How are you using Sure?\n\n- [ ] I was a paying Maybe customer (hosted version)\n- [ ] I use it on PikaPod, Umbrel or similar (VPS included)\n- [x] I am a self-hosted user (local only)\n\n### Self hoster checklist\n\n- Self hosted app commit SHA (find in user menu): `89f42497`\n  - [x] I have confirmed that my app's commit is the latest version of Sure\n- Where are you hosting?\n  - [ ] Render\n  - [x] Docker Compose\n  - [ ] Umbrel\n  - [ ] PikaPod\n  - [ ] Other (please specify)\n\n---\n\n## Bug description\n\n`IdentifyRecurringTransactionsJob#family_has_incomplete_syncs?` (`app/jobs/identify_recurring_transactions_job.rb:45-60`) is the debounce gate that delays `RecurringTransaction::Identifier` until the family's in-flight provider syncs have settled. The gate hand-rolls the list of provider `*_items` associations it polls, and the list is incomplete: it only checks `plaid_items`, `simplefin_items`, `lunchflow_items`, `enable_banking_items`, and `sophtron_items`. Nine other provider integrations that are also `Syncable` and have a `has_many :*_items` declaration on `Family` are silently missing from the gate: `coinbase_items`, `binance_items`, `kraken_items`, `coinstats_items`, `snaptrade_items`, `mercury_items`, `brex_items`, `indexa_capital_items`, `ibkr_items`.\n\nWhen a sync on one of these nine providers is still in flight, the gate falls through, `RecurringTransaction::Identifier` runs against a partial dataset, and any recurring pattern that needs \u2265 3 occurrences silently misses the in-flight batch. When the late-arriving sync finishes it (correctly) re-schedules the job, but the previous run has already written a `RecurringTransaction` row with a stale `occurrence_count` / `last_occurrence_date`; the second run hits the `find_or_initialize_by` upsert path and the counts written reflect only the in-window entries seen at that moment, not the full set.\n\nThe maintainers' own `Sync.for_family` helper (`app/models/sync.rb:61-75`) already enumerates every `*_items` association via `Family.reflect_on_all_associations(:has_many)` filtered by inclusion of the `Syncable` module \u2014 that is exactly the helper this gate should delegate to so the list cannot drift again. The same drift pattern has already happened once: the file has had a single edit since creation (Apr 19, 2026, when Sophtron was bolted on as the 5th entry of the now-out-of-date hand-rolled list).\n\n### Bypass / drift surface (current code)\n\n```ruby\n# app/jobs/identify_recurring_transactions_job.rb:45-60\ndef family_has_incomplete_syncs?(family)\n  # Check family's own syncs\n  return true if family.syncs.incomplete.exists?\n\n  # Check all provider items' syncs\n  return true if family.plaid_items.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists?         if family.respond_to?(:plaid_items)\n  return true if family.simplefin_items.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists?     if family.respond_to?(:simplefin_items)\n  return true if family.lunchflow_items.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists?     if family.respond_to?(:lunchflow_items)\n  return true if family.enable_banking_items.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists? if family.respond_to?(:enable_banking_items)\n  return true if family.sophtron_items.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists?      if family.respond_to?(:sophtron_items)\n\n  # Check accounts' syncs\n  return true if family.accounts.joins(:syncs).merge(Sync.incomplete).exists?\n\n  false\nend\n```\n\n`Family` (`app/models/family.rb:3-5`) actually includes 14 `*Connectable` concerns: `PlaidConnectable`, `SimplefinConnectable`, `LunchflowConnectable`, `EnableBankingConnectable`, `CoinbaseConnectable`, `BinanceConnectable`, `KrakenConnectable`, `CoinstatsConnectable`, `SnaptradeConnectable`, `MercuryConnectable`, `BrexConnectable`, `SophtronConnectable`, `IndexaCapitalConnectable`, `IbkrConnectable`. Each `*Connectable` declares `has_many :*_items, dependent: :destroy`. The gate covers 5 of those 14.\n\n### To Reproduce\n\nSteps to reproduce the behavior:\n\n1. Run a self-hosted Sure instance with at least one provider that the gate does **not** cover (e.g. Coinbase, Mercury, Brex, Snaptrade).\n2. Connect that provider so the family has at least one `*_items` row (e.g. `family.coinbase_items.first`).\n3. Trigger a sync on that item so a `Sync` row in state `syncing` exists on it. The easiest dev-mode trigger:\n   ```ruby\n   family.coinbase_items.first.sync_later  # or .syncing! the most recent sync directly\n   ```\n4. While that sync is still in `syncing` (before the worker finishes), enqueue or manually `perform_now` an `IdentifyRecurringTransactionsJob` for the same family.\n5. Observe that the job runs `RecurringTransaction::Identifier#identify_recurring_patterns` even though a provider sync is in flight. Expected: the job should debounce until every in-flight `Syncable` finishes, exactly as it does today for Plaid / Simplefin / Lunchflow / Enable Banking / Sophtron.\n\nEquivalent Minitest reproduction (against existing fixtures):\n\n```ruby\nrequire \"test_helper\"\n\nclass IdentifyRecurringTransactionsJobReproTest < ActiveJob::TestCase\n  test \"waits for in-flight Coinbase provider syncs (today: does not)\" do\n    family = families(:dylan_family)\n    family.update!(recurring_transactions_disabled: false) if family.respond_to?(:recurring_transactions_disabled)\n\n    coinbase_item = family.coinbase_items.create!(\n      name: \"Coinbase Test\",\n      api_key: SecureRandom.hex(16),\n      api_secret: SecureRandom.hex(16)\n    )\n    Sync.create!(syncable: coinbase_item, status: \"syncing\")\n\n    # Today: the identifier runs anyway because the gate doesn't poll coinbase_items.\n    # After the fix: the next assertion passes because the gate returns true.\n    RecurringTransaction::Identifier.any_instance.expects(:identify_recurring_patterns).never\n\n    IdentifyRecurringTransactionsJob.new.perform(family.id, (Time.current.to_f + 1))\n  end\nend\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe gate should poll **every** `Syncable` provider association on `Family`, not five of them. The cleanest fix is to delete the hand-rolled list and delegate to `Sync.for_family(family).incomplete.exists?` (or a small wrapper class method such as `Sync.any_incomplete_for?(family)`), which uses the existing `family_syncable_associations` reflection helper. Then no provider integration added in the future can silently regress this gate again \u2014 the same reflection helper is already trusted by `Sync.for_family`'s own implementation at `app/models/sync.rb:61-75`, so the contract is already established in this codebase.\n\nCache-of-symptoms summary, for each missing provider:\n\n| Provider concern (in `app/models/family/`) | Association declared | Polled by gate today? |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `coinbase_connectable.rb` | `has_many :coinbase_items` | \u274c |\n| `binance_connectable.rb` | `has_many :binance_items` | \u274c |\n| `kraken_connectable.rb` | `has_many :kraken_items` | \u274c |\n| `coinstats_connectable.rb` | `has_many :coinstats_items` | \u274c |\n| `snaptrade_connectable.rb` | `has_many :snaptrade_items` | \u274c |\n| `mercury_connectable.rb` | `has_many :mercury_items` | \u274c |\n| `brex_connectable.rb` | `has_many :brex_items` | \u274c |\n| `indexa_capital_connectable.rb` | `has_many :indexa_capital_items` | \u274c |\n| `ibkr_connectable.rb` | `has_many :ibkr_items` | \u274c |\n\nThe user-visible impact is strongest on Mercury / Brex (business banking, real recurring expenses where partial-batch identification corrupts the `occurrence_count`) and on Snaptrade (investment transactions feeding into the recurring pattern detection). Pure-crypto providers (Coinbase / Binance / Kraken / Coinstats) feed `Trade` rows that the identifier already excludes by `entryable_type` filter, so the visible regression there is narrower \u2014 but the gate-drift is the same shape across all nine.\n\n### Screenshots and/or recordings\n\nNot applicable \u2014 this is a background-job / sync-state bug; reproduction is observable from the Rails console or by adding the Minitest above. The user-visible symptom (a `RecurringTransaction` row with an `occurrence_count` lower than what the eventual full dataset would have produced) only surfaces in the UI after the partial-batch run, and is visually indistinguishable from \"pattern doesn't have enough occurrences yet\" \u2014 operators usually attribute it to the data, not the gate.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-27T22:01:35.000Z",
